observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management require the Accounting and General Services Office to:
a) Compare and reconcile their records and correct/adjust whatever discrepancies;
b) Record in the book of accounts those properties found in the official station/office which are not recorded in the GL/SL, but included in the physical count and still owned by the agency;
c) Identify properties no longer serviceable and adjust their records; and
d) Reconcile their records regularly/periodically using the cost of properties, instead of book value for easy detection of any discrepancies/unreconciled items, and effect corresponding adjustments promptly, in compliance with Section 53(b) of GAAM, Volume III.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive;
a) Require the General Services Officer, Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Assessor to reconcile their records and coordinate with the Registry of Deeds for the titled lots in the name of the Municipality; and
b) Instruct the Municipal Assessor to prioritize the registration and transfer of title of the land owned by the Municipality to fully protect its interest.

We recommended and the BAC agreed to:

furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Contract Agreement and its attachments within five calendar days from execution thereof as required under Section 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 23, 2009;

observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to ensure adherence to the principles of transparency, competitiveness and public monitoring;

strengthen internal control over the evaluation of bids and post-qualification of bidders; 

prepare the required documents/reports with extra care to avoid errors which could mislead reader and users of the reports; and 

submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and address the deficiencies enumerated.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:

require the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to ensure the inclusion of duly appropriated COVID-19 related PPAs in the AIP of the Municipality in compliance with the provisions of the DILG - DBM JMC No. 02 dated March 30, 2020 and COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012;

submit the necessary documents to support the grant of daily COVID-19 Hazard Pay to officials and employees and job order workers during the entire ECQ period including holidays and written authority allowing the Municipal front liners to physically report for work during ECQ as provided in Unnumbered Memoranda dated March 16, 2020 and April 7, 2020 and Civil Service Commission (CSC) Announcement No. 13, s. 2020 dated March 17, 2020, otherwise, payments not in consonance with the issued guidelines will be disallowed in audit; 

require the BAC to observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and other pertinent GPPB issuances in all its succeeding procurement activities during State of Emergency so as to avoid doubts on the integrity of its procurement;

require the Municipal Accountant to (i) review the regularity and completeness of supporting documents of disbursement vouchers before processing claims for payment; (ii) submit the lacking documents noted above; and (iii) observe the use of proper accounts in the recording of the financial transactions of the LGU; and




require the Local Finance Committee to adhere with the posting and reporting requirements for Bayanihan Grant provided under Items 4.3 and 4.4 of DBM Local Budget Circular No. 125 dated April 7, 2020 and copy furnish the Audit Team of the monthly reports and written notice to the oversight bodies.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that:

The Municipal Mayor along with the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and Municipal Engineer strictly follow the provisions of DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1 in planning the PPAs funded under the 20 percent DF and their implementation. Closely monitor the implementation of development projects and see to it that priority projects identified in the AIP are promptly implemented in order to deliver satisfactory benefits to the constituents; 

The Municipal Engineer conduct applicable detailed engineering activities to serve as basis of the MPDC in properly evaluating the technical viability of proposed projects before inclusion in the list of priority projects to be included in the 20 percent DF.  In this way, projects with issues, not feasible or has a remote possibility of being implemented may not be considered during the budget year;

The MPDC ensure that PPAs incorporated in the AIP partake the nature of investment or capital expenditure and that the same would contribute to the attainment of socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes of the Municipality;

The BAC  (i) furnish the Audit Team with a copy of Contracts/Purchase Orders and their attachments within five working days from execution/issuance as required under Sections 3.1.1 and 3.2.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001; (ii) observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 so as to avoid doubts on the integrity of its bidding process; (iii) prepare the required reports/documents with extra care to avoid errors which could mislead readers and users of the reports; and (iv) submit written explanations relative to the deficiencies noted above; 

The ICO-Municipal Accountant (i) be guided by  the requirements of Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 474 b(5) of R.A. No. 7160 for proper documentation of claims against government funds; (ii) submit the lacking documents mentioned above to establish the propriety of the disbursements; and (iii) observe the proper use of account in recording transactions and effect the necessary correcting entry for proper presentation of the accounts in the financial statements; and

The Municipal Budget Officer be circumspect in monitoring the charges against the 20 percent DF and see to it that payments were charged in the projects’ specific appropriation.

We recommended that the:

a.	Municipal Mayor, MSWDO and Municipal Accountant submit written explanation and/or pertinent documents to prove that a mere referral letter from one of the members of the SB fully satisfy the requirement of SB Resolution No. 2018-08 and if it constitutes a valid authorization in the grant of cash assistance in excess of the maximum limit, otherwise, observe the maximum limit of cash assistance to be granted to the recipients or request appropriate SB proceedings to authorize the grant of same;

b.	Municipal Mayor request the SB to establish a clear cut guidelines, policies and procedures on the selection and grant of livelihood assistance within the Municipality and adopt a system of monitoring and inspection of the projects;

c.	MSWDO indicate in the assessment/evaluation report the amount of cash assistance to be given to the individuals in crisis situation in compliance with the existing guidelines;

d.	Municipal Mayor and MSWDO ensure that financial assistance shall be immediately released once the amount has been determined based on the interview/assessment and submitted supporting documents as provided under DSWD Memorandum Circular No. 2; and

e.	Municipal Mayor, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer strictly observed the required procedures in the disbursements of funds.

We recommended and the management agreed to:

a.	conduct regular monitoring of the implementation of the plan and other relevant laws/ordinances within the Municipality’s jurisdiction to ensure the effectiveness of the solid waste management programs. Impose appropriate sanction where necessary;




b.	through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the Municipality by educating their respective constituents through Information Education Campaign (IEC) on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes and the importance of their participation  in the implementation various SWM programs;

c.	evaluate the current composition of the MSWMB and look for possible members that could qualify to complete the line up; and



d.	through SWMB, stop the operation in an open dump site as final garbage disposal facility, instead prioritize the processing of various requirements for its conversion into a sanitary landfill in compliance with Sections 40 and 41 of R.A. No. 9003 the soonest possible time to avert adverse environmental consequences.

We recommended and the management agreed that the Municipal Mayor:

a.	require the ICO-Municipal Accountant to give priority to the timely submission of the accounts within the period required under COA Circular No. 2009-006 dated September 15, 2009 and COA Circular No. 95-006 dated May 18, 1995 to enable the Audit Team to conduct timely audit thereof;

b.	require the former and incumbent ICO-Municipal Accountants to work hand in hand and set aside their differences as such lapses incurred would not only redound to their personal loss but of the Municipality and the people whom they are mandated to serve.  Submit immediately the unsubmitted accounts and financial reports, otherwise, enforce the suspension of salaries of erring personnel pursuant to Section 122 of PD No. 1445.  It is to be emphasized that non-submission of the lacking disbursement vouchers and payroll as well as relevant supporting documents shall warrant the outright issuance of Notices of Disallowance without prejudice to any administrative disciplinary action that may be instituted against the accountable officers as provided under Section 39 (3) of PD No. 1445; 

c.	require proper turn-over of all documents and reports from the outgoing to incoming officers/employees so as to establish proper accountability and to secure all documents for future references and proper reporting; and

d.	ensure that appropriate actions are taken on the deficiencies noted in audit as well as on various communications received.

We recommended and the management agreed that:

a.	The Municipal Budget Officer prepare and attached in the Annual Budget the AIP Summary Form prescribed under Annex E of the BOM for LGUs to ensure that PPAs to be implemented during the year shall reflect the actual amount provided in the approved budget;

b.	 The Municipal Mayor along with the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) and Municipal Engineer strictly follow the provisions of DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1 in planning the PPAs funded under the 20 percent DF and their implementation.  Closely monitor the implementation of development projects and see to it that priority projects identified in the AIP are promptly implemented in order to deliver satisfactory benefits to the constituents; 

c.	The MPDC ensure that PPAs incorporated in the AIP partake the nature of investment or capital expenditure and that the same would contribute to the attainment of socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes of the Municipality;

d.	The BAC to (i) furnish the Audit Team with a copy of Contracts/Purchase Orders and their attachments within five working days from execution/issuance as required under Sections 3.1.1 and 3.2.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001; (ii) observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 so as to avoid doubts on the integrity of its bidding process; (iii) prepare the required reports/documents with extra care to avoid errors which could mislead readers and users of the reports; and (iv) submit written explanations relative to the deficiencies noted above; and

e.	The ICO-Municipal Accountant (i) be guided by  the requirements of Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 474 b(5) of R.A. No. 7160 for proper documentation of claims against government funds; (ii) submit the lacking documents mentioned above to establish the propriety of the disbursements; and (iii) observe the proper use of account in recording transactions and effect the necessary correcting entry for proper presentation of the accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management:

Through the MSWD Officer conduct proper verification and validation of the targeted beneficiaries;

Ensure that the ESP and other similar benefits be granted to duly qualified recipients observing the prohibitions stated in DSWD MC No. 09, Series of 2020; 

Cause the immediate refund of the amount paid to beneficiaries who were not qualified to receive the grant by informing them through writing;

Upon receipt of the refunded amounts, cause the redistribution to identified eligible beneficiaries, if warranted;

Through the MSWD Office to introduce more control and tools such as but not limited to:

Assign staff only to consolidate and deduplicate all target beneficiaries in San Andres before uploading them to the DSWD FO;

Provide copies of written instructions on filling out the SAC forms with complete and accurate information to prevent duplication of entry in the master list when ran for deduplication. Should the beneficiary is unable to write; the barangay council shall provide assistance; and

Create simplified and summarized guidelines to be issued by the DSWD to be given to all PBs and urge them to reproduce more copies for their information campaign within their jurisdiction. 

Through the Office of the Mayor and MSWD Office to:

Urge all PBs to maintain close coordination and communication with their constituents to deter people from taking advantage of the weakness in the system; 

Encourage potential recipients to uphold guidelines to mitigate issues and avoid administrative cases that may be filed against them; and

Request the cooperation and utmost support of all barangay officials to achieve a high success rate in implementing various programs of the LGU and the National Government.

Encourage various LGU offices such as but not limited to the MSWD Office, MDRRM Office, Municipal Agriculture Office, Rural Health Unit, and Municipal Planning and Development Office to create a task force with their respective offices as members. Together with the assistance of all barangay officials and coordination with the Philippine Statistics Office, the task force will conduct an unannounced family profiling not tied to a specific program to mitigate the deliberate misrepresentation of any person and design a database that will contain the records and necessary information of families in the municipality of San Andres. The National and Local Government will use this system for implementation of future projects and derive benefits therefrom in various ways such as but not limited to:

List of all families requiring relief goods in times of crisis and state of calamity. The LGU can readily quantify the number of goods needed to be procured and speed up the distribution process;

Speed up the identification of targeted beneficiaries who require specific support from the government and maintain records of families that already received or constantly receiving assistance;

Deter individuals in taking advantage of any program by deceiving any personnel attached to a government office;

Eliminate chances of double payment of assistance; and

Capture the actual population of the municipality, and the information gathered may be used for statistical purposes and for other legal purposes.

Based on the foregoing audit observations, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a.	require all accountable officers and employees to immediately settle their outstanding cash advances; 

b.	exert extra efforts to recover outstanding cash advances from accountable officers who are no longer in the service nor connected with the municipality;

c.	direct the Municipal Accountant to refrain from granting additional cash advances to any official or employee unless previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, pursuant to Section 4.1.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;

d.	stop the grant of special cash advances to elected officials and employees not designated as disbursing officer; 

e.	require the officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period provided in Section 5 of COA Circular 97-002; and

f.	submit the documents supporting the liquidation of cash advances totaling P6,508,500.00.

We reiterated our recommendation and the management agreed that the ICO-Municipal Accountant:

a.	strictly observe the monthly preparation of Bank Reconciliation Statements to validate the balance of the Cash in Bank account in the financial statements, in compliance with Section 3 of COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996;

b.	exert diligent effort in identifying the individual reconciling items presented in the BRS by preparing schedules and/or details of the amount presented in lump sum;

c.	submit the bank statements and other relevant documents showing that the identified reconciling items were properly recorded and adjusted in the books of accounts; and

d.	maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for each depository account to substantiate the validity and correctness of balances of each account and to easily monitor the transactions affecting those accounts.

