We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

ICO-Municipal Accountant to set up RPT/SET Receivables in accordance with Section 20 of NGAS Manual, Volume I; 

ICO-Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant at the beginning of the year with a duly certified list of Real Property Taxpayers showing the names of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year; and 

Municipal Assessor to furnish the Treasurer with the latest valuations of property of each taxpayer;

We recommended that:
the Municipal Mayor, through its Inventory Committee, conduct complete physical count of the properties of the Municipality, reconcile the results of the count with the accounting records and submit the complete and accurate RPCPPE to the Audit Team, pursuant to Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1;
the Municipal Accountant observe the proper accounting for transfer of PPE accounts. Prepare the necessary adjustment to correct the balances of the affected accounts in the Statement of Financial Position of General Fund;
the ICO-Municipal Accountant effect the prompt transfer of the cost of completed project from the Trust Fund to the General Fund books.
the ICO- Municipal Accountant effect the necessary adjusting entry for the transfer of the costs of the 37 completed projects from CIP accounts to Infrastructure Assets and Buildings and Other Structures accounts;
the ICO-Municipal Accountant provide depreciation for all depreciable Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE) as provided under Section 4(o) of the NGAS Manuel for LGU, Volume 1 to establish proper valuation of PPE accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:           
a. Require all accountable officers and employees to immediately liquidate their outstanding cash advances; 
b. Exert extra efforts to recover outstanding cash advances from Accountable Officers who are no longer in the service nor connected with the municipality; 
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to refrain from granting additional cash advances to any official or employee unless previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, pursuant to Section 4.1.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
d. Require the officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period provided in Section 5 of COA Circular 97-002;
e. Instruct the ICO Municipal Accountant to Reclassify “Due from Officers and Employees” account to “Advances to Officers and Employees” in compliance with the Revised Chart of Account to present the correct account title in the Financial Statements (FS) and to trace the discrepancy noted in the balance of cash advances per book and per audit. Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjustment to correct the balance presented in the FS; and
f.  Require strictly an Office Clearance from Money and Property accountabilities, pursuant to Sections 200 and 256, Vol. I of the Government Accounting and Auditing Manual from all personnel who seek retirement, resignation, transfer or claim for death benefits in order that all accountabilities could be appropriately settled.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
direct the submission of MSWMP to the Provincial Solid Waste Management Board for review and for approval by the National Solid Waste Management Commission;
evaluate the current composition of the MSWMB and look for possible members that could qualify to complete the line up; 
stop the operation on open dump site for its garbage disposal, instead, develop a sanitary landfill as final garbage disposal site of the LGU; and
instruct the municipal officials concerned to review the budget set for Solid Waste Management for the effective and efficient performance of its programs and activities.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor instruct the MPDO, with the assistance of the Municipal GFPS to:
• Institutionalize the GAD database with adequate and systematically gathered sex-disaggregated data which will provide the bases for gender analysis, planning, programming and policy formulation;
• Undertake gender analysis to identify and confirm existing gender issues and ensure that the programs, projects and activities are responsive to the said issues;
• Revisit Annex B of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 which identifies the data requirements for particular gender issues; and
• Include in the GAD Plan and Budget the attendance to seminar and training of the personnel assigned in the GAD as well as the expenses related to development of GAD Database.

We recommended that the ICO-Municipal Accountant: 
strictly observe the monthly preparation of Bank Reconciliation Statements to validate the balance of the Cash in Bank account in 40 the financial statements, in compliance with Section 3 of COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996;
 exert diligent effort in reconciling the book and bank balances and submit the BRS and other relevant documents showing that the identified reconciling items were properly recorded and adjusted in the books of accounts;
reconcile accounting records with the cash book of the ICO-Municipal Treasurer. Henceforth, both offices should reconcile their records regularly so that errors or discrepancies that may be noted could be readily adjusted; and
maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for each depository account to substantiate the validity and correctness of the balances of each account and to easily monitor the transactions affecting those accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:
the ICO-Municipal Accountant to set up RPT/SET Receivables in accordance with Section 20 of NGAS Manual, Volume I; 
the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant at the beginning of the year with a duly certified list of Real Property Taxpayers showing the names of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year; and 
the Municipal Assessor to furnish the Treasurer with the latest valuations of property of each taxpayer;

We recommended that the Local   Chief   Executive   require:
The Accountant and General      Services Officer to complete the reconciliation     process to eliminate the discrepancies in the inventory report and accounting records;
The Accountant to prepare adjusting and reclassifying entries on the following:
To recognize in the books the unrecorded PPEs;
To derecognize from the books items that should be directly charged to expense including demolished structures; and;
To reclassify PPEs to appropriate accounts.
The General Services Officer to correct the erroneous classification of PPEs presented in Annex A in his inventory report and transfer recording of all unserviceable items (Annex B) in IIRUP.
We also recommended the immediate and proper disposal of unserviceable properties pursuant to Section 79 of P.D. 1445 and par. V of COA Circular No. 89-296.

We recommended to the Local     Chief Executive to require the    Municipal Treasurer:
submit all missing disbursement vouchers to the accounting      office for proper recording in the books of the LGU;
prepare the RCI containing all checks issued during the period and submit this to the Accounting Office together with corresponding DVs;
ensure that complete supporting documents are attached to the DVs before the paid transactions are transmitted to the accounting office; and
observe the ninety (90) day period within which to submit the missing DVs before suspensions mature into disallowance.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant prepare and record JEV upon receipt of DVs and supporting documents to adjust and correct balances of the affected accounts.

We recommended that Management:
Adopt the guidelines promulgated by DSWD in the selection of AICS beneficiaries and in setting up of the maximum amount or ceiling for each type or kind of financial assistance;
Ensure that only the DSWD personnel assess and evaluate applicants requesting financial assistance out of AICS program including the identification of nearest kin who serve as the claimant;
Provide specific budget in the Office of the MSWD for the AICS program; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to be more circumspect in reviewing completeness of supporting documents paying attention on erasures and signatures.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive requires:

1. The Accountant and General Services Officers to reconcile the discrepancies between the inventory report and accounting records;

2. The Accountant and General Service Officers to make adjustments in their books on error in classifying of the items to be recorded in the books;

3. Unserviceable items should be properly reported in IIRUP and the same be disposed; and

4. Classify the items to appropriate PPE accounts.
